05760nam a22009255i 9783110576214DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20192020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831105762147 a10.1515/97831105762142doi  a(DE-B1597)489503  a(OCoLC)1129194862  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aREL0170002bisacsh1 aTriplett, Katja, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBuddhism and Medicine in Japan :bA Topical Survey (500-1600 CE) of a Complex Relationship /cKatja Triplett. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2019] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (XV, 259 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion and Society ,x1437-5370 ;v8100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue -- tAcknowledgements -- tConventions -- tIntroduction -- t1. Buddhism, Medicine and Magic: The Boundary Problem -- t2. Operating with Buddhism -- t3. The Eye I: An Organ as a Site of Empowerment and Healing -- t4. The Eye II: Buddhist Healing and Living with Visual Impairment -- t5. Women: Care of the Reproductive Female Body -- t6. Plants: Materia medica, Medicinal Gardens and Panaceas -- t7. Horses and Equine Medicine -- tConclusion: Boundaries, Maps and Types of Othering -- tTimeline -- tList of Images -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book demonstrates the close link between medicine and Buddhism in early and medieval Japan. It may seem difficult to think of Japanese Buddhism as being linked to the realm of medical practices since religious healing is usually thought to be restricted to prayers for divine intervention. There is a surprising lack of scholarship regarding medicinal practices in Japanese Buddhism although an overwhelming amount of primary sources proves otherwise. A careful re-reading of well-known materials from a study-of-religions perspective, together with in some cases a first-time exploration of manuscripts and prints, opens new views on an understudied field. The book presents a topical survey and comprises chapters on treating sight-related diseases, women’s health, plant-based materica medica and medicinal gardens, and finally horse medicine to include veterinary knowledge. Terminological problems faced in working on this material – such as ‘religious’ or ‘magical healing’ as opposed to ‘secular medicine’ – are assessed. The book suggests focusing more on the plural nature of the Japanese healing system as encountered in the primary sources and reconsidering the use of categories from the European intellectual tradition.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aBuddhismus. 4aJapan. 4aMedizin. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  aJapanese Buddhism.  aJapanese religions.  ahistory of medicine in Japan.  areligion and medicine.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE  DG 2019 Englishz978311061685908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig. Stud., Jewish Stud.2019 Englishz978311061074108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theology, Relig. Studies, Jewish Studies 2019z9783110606508oZDB-23-DGF08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertReligious Studies De Gruyterz97831107168250 cEPUBz97831105755690 cprintz978311057350340